WEBVTT

00:06.798 --> 00:09.927
- Tonight, "Forged in Fire"
brings twice the heat,

00:09.927 --> 00:12.095
twice the blood,
sweat, and tears,

00:12.095 --> 00:14.264
as four top bladesmiths

00:14.264 --> 00:15.891
compete alongside
their apprentices

00:15.891 --> 00:16.808
in the ultimate
team challenge.

00:16.808 --> 00:18.894
- There! Yeah!

00:18.894 --> 00:20.312
- Each pair will be tested
like never before...

00:20.312 --> 00:22.314
- Grind it.
[bleep] it. Grind it.

00:22.314 --> 00:23.524
- And they'll either
work together...

00:23.524 --> 00:24.816
- Really done well.

00:24.816 --> 00:26.276
- Or go down in flames.

00:26.276 --> 00:28.237
- We don't have time
to [bleep] around.

00:28.237 --> 00:30.656
- With double the stakes
and $10,000 on the line,

00:30.656 --> 00:32.199
who will be crowned
the "Forged in Fire"

00:32.199 --> 00:34.701
ultimate team champions?

00:34.701 --> 00:38.121
[dramatic music]

00:40.207 --> 00:42.584
♪ ♪

00:42.584 --> 00:45.003
- My name's Joe Calton,
I'm 39 years old,

00:45.003 --> 00:46.880
and I'm from Cheyenne, Wyoming.

00:46.880 --> 00:49.258
- I'm Casey Perdue.
I like working with Joe.

00:49.258 --> 00:51.134
He lets you make
your own mistakes,

00:51.134 --> 00:53.095
but he also shows you
how to correct them.

00:53.095 --> 00:54.763
He said a Mastersmith
means nothing

00:54.763 --> 00:56.765
other than you made
all the mistakes

00:56.765 --> 00:59.184
and figured out
how to fix 'em.

00:59.184 --> 01:01.061
- I'm Raleigh Desiato.

01:01.061 --> 01:02.354
I've been making blades
for 12 years,

01:02.354 --> 01:03.730
horseshoe knives mainly.

01:03.730 --> 01:05.607
- And I am Kelly Gregory.

01:05.607 --> 01:07.401
I have been making blades
seriously for a year.

01:07.401 --> 01:09.987
- Kelly's such a bad cat.
When you work with somebody,

01:09.987 --> 01:12.447
you get, like, this--your own
little, like, language.

01:12.447 --> 01:14.116
Dude, we are, like,
totally telepathic,

01:14.116 --> 01:15.701
ESPN, or whatever.

01:15.701 --> 01:17.369
- We are gonna kick
everybody's ass.

01:17.369 --> 01:19.621
- And we do the--
[both imitate explosion]

01:19.621 --> 01:23.000
- My name is Tyler Adkins.
I'm also known as Iron Man.

01:23.000 --> 01:24.543
I've been bladesmithing
for 12 years.

01:24.543 --> 01:26.336
- I'm Leon Vanguard.

01:26.336 --> 01:28.171
2005 is when
I first met Iron Man.

01:28.171 --> 01:30.173
I had to call his house.
I asked for Iron Man,

01:30.173 --> 01:31.842
and the person
on the phone goes, "Who?"

01:31.842 --> 01:34.886
I went, "Skinny white guy
that likes metal."

01:34.886 --> 01:36.555
She goes, "Tyler!"

01:36.555 --> 01:38.098
- Yep. Yeah, that was my mom.

01:38.098 --> 01:40.100
- My name is Mark J. Hopper.

01:40.100 --> 01:42.519
I teach smithing
in Atlanta, Georgia.

01:42.519 --> 01:44.521
- My name is
Jessica D. Collins,

01:44.521 --> 01:46.982
and I've been apprenticing
with Mark for 4 years.

01:46.982 --> 01:49.318
Eventually, I got good enough

01:49.318 --> 01:51.486
to help him actually
design the classes.

01:51.486 --> 01:53.613
- This is almost at that point

01:53.613 --> 01:56.033
when a master
turns to his apprentice

01:56.033 --> 01:59.286
and goes, "It's time
to become a journeyman."

01:59.286 --> 02:02.664
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

02:02.664 --> 02:04.708
The eight of you
will be competing

02:04.708 --> 02:07.002
for the title of
"Forged in Fire" champion

02:07.002 --> 02:09.212
and checks for $10,000,

02:09.212 --> 02:12.049
all in front of our panel
of expert judges:

02:12.049 --> 02:14.468
Two-time "Forged in Fire"
champion, Ben Abbott;

02:14.468 --> 02:17.596
historic weapons re-creation
specialist, David Baker;

02:17.596 --> 02:21.266
edged weapons specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

02:21.266 --> 02:22.976
On your anvils is a cloth.

02:22.976 --> 02:24.019
Remove it.

02:24.019 --> 02:26.521
♪ ♪

02:26.521 --> 02:30.150
That is a 2x6 round of W1,

02:30.150 --> 02:32.736
from which you will
forge your blades.

02:32.736 --> 02:34.488
And not signature blades.

02:34.488 --> 02:36.907
Instead, we're kicking things
up a notch.

02:36.907 --> 02:41.203
Today, you will forge
an iconic weapon of warfare:

02:41.203 --> 02:42.996
the trench knife.

02:42.996 --> 02:45.165
- Cool, we're making
trench knives!

02:45.165 --> 02:46.958
What the [bleep]'s
a trench knife?

02:46.958 --> 02:48.377
- The trench knife
was developed

02:48.377 --> 02:50.128
for U. S. World War I troops

02:50.128 --> 02:51.922
in need of a versatile
weapon to employ

02:51.922 --> 02:53.590
in the hand-to-hand
combat they faced

02:53.590 --> 02:55.175
while raiding enemy trenches.

02:55.175 --> 02:56.968
Featuring a pointed blade

02:56.968 --> 02:58.970
and four-fingered guard,
or knuckle duster,

02:58.970 --> 03:00.764
the weapon was used
for stabbing,

03:00.764 --> 03:02.265
slashing, and punching.

03:02.265 --> 03:04.059
The solid steel knuckle duster

03:04.059 --> 03:05.769
prevented enemies
from seizing the knife,

03:05.769 --> 03:07.229
and could be used
like brass knuckles

03:07.229 --> 03:09.147
to issue devastating blows.

03:09.147 --> 03:11.858
Your knives must include
an integral handle

03:11.858 --> 03:13.860
made from the same piece
of steel as the blade.

03:13.860 --> 03:16.530
You must include
four finger holes.

03:16.530 --> 03:18.115
Keep in mind that
in the second round,

03:18.115 --> 03:20.033
you'll be putting scales
on those handles

03:20.033 --> 03:21.785
to turn them into
fully functional weapons

03:21.785 --> 03:23.662
that will be tested
for strength and durability

03:23.662 --> 03:25.580
in a fuel can stab,

03:25.580 --> 03:28.792
and for sharpness
in a fire hose slice.

03:28.792 --> 03:31.420
You will have four hours
in which to complete this,

03:31.420 --> 03:34.047
but only one of you can be
working the steel at a time,

03:34.047 --> 03:36.800
so we will rotate
at 30 minute intervals.

03:36.800 --> 03:38.301
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:38.301 --> 03:40.512
Apprentices, you're up first.

03:40.512 --> 03:42.931
Your four-hour forging time
starts...

03:42.931 --> 03:43.974
now.

03:43.974 --> 03:46.643
♪ ♪

03:46.643 --> 03:49.771
- Get as many bricks
into your fire as possible.

03:49.771 --> 03:51.731
- Pick up a hammer,
get a good feel for it.

03:51.731 --> 03:53.567
Which one
are you gonna use first?

03:53.567 --> 03:55.277
- So are the masters
stuck in one place?

03:55.277 --> 03:57.320
- They're supposed to
stay in their slot.

03:57.320 --> 04:00.031
- A lot of bodies, hot steel.

04:00.031 --> 04:01.950
Safety is paramount.

04:01.950 --> 04:04.202
♪ ♪

04:04.202 --> 04:06.371
- Get it back in there.
Go find some bigger tongs.

04:06.371 --> 04:08.457
We're so used to forging
against the clock,

04:08.457 --> 04:10.959
being in horseshoeing
contests...

04:10.959 --> 04:12.502
- This one?
- There you go!

04:12.502 --> 04:14.129
That it's kind of
old rap for us, I think.

04:14.129 --> 04:16.131
- It's fun.
- Yeah, it's fun.

04:16.131 --> 04:17.883
- Yeah, it's fun.
- It's what we do for fun.

04:17.883 --> 04:19.217
Hey, can you block
the outside up a little bit?

04:19.217 --> 04:20.969
- Yeah, I can.

04:20.969 --> 04:22.721
- And then open up
your tools here.

04:22.721 --> 04:24.514
Am I being too bossy?
- No, no, keep talking.

04:24.514 --> 04:26.725
- Longer footsteps!
You gotta let it press.

04:26.725 --> 04:28.852
There! Yeah!

04:28.852 --> 04:31.062
- I see a lot of, uh,
intense coaching from Raleigh.

04:31.062 --> 04:33.398
- There you go!

04:33.398 --> 04:34.941
Yeah!

04:34.941 --> 04:36.401
[laughter]

04:36.401 --> 04:38.195
That's [bleep] awesome.

04:38.195 --> 04:39.905
- How long should I wait?
About 30 seconds?

04:39.905 --> 04:41.490
- No, don't time it.

04:41.490 --> 04:43.617
Look. Always look.

04:43.617 --> 04:45.577
Well, Leon is up first...
- [chuckles]

04:45.577 --> 04:47.788
- And that poses a challenge,

04:47.788 --> 04:50.040
because I didn't have a chance
to prep anything on this one.

04:50.040 --> 04:51.750
- Said you were gonna prep it.

04:51.750 --> 04:53.084
You said you're gonna prep it.
- [laughs]

04:53.084 --> 04:55.128
You're gonna need
some mechanical help.

04:55.128 --> 04:56.755
- I'm a little nervous,
'cause I have never worked with

04:56.755 --> 04:59.424
power hammers before.
- Up! Down! Up! Down!

04:59.424 --> 05:02.219
- It's actually drying out.
I love this.

05:02.219 --> 05:04.471
Power tools.
- Good job, Leon.

05:04.471 --> 05:05.597
- Thank you.
- Good job.

05:05.597 --> 05:08.141
You did--you're doing good.

05:08.141 --> 05:10.977
- I am a little nervous

05:10.977 --> 05:13.063
that I have to go first.

05:13.063 --> 05:15.148
- Just break it down
as far as you can.

05:15.148 --> 05:18.527
- I want to get this thing
into the perfect position

05:18.527 --> 05:22.572
for Mark to start the isolation
on the handle and blade.

05:22.572 --> 05:23.907
- Look at Jessica's
billet, man.

05:23.907 --> 05:25.659
It is beautiful.

05:25.659 --> 05:27.452
- I have never made
a trench knife.

05:27.452 --> 05:29.412
Mark has the experience.

05:29.412 --> 05:31.206
He's been doing it
a lot longer than I have.

05:31.206 --> 05:33.625
- Would you give me
a 5-inch mark there as well?

05:33.625 --> 05:35.794
- I'm gonna follow his lead.

05:35.794 --> 05:37.254
- Switch!
- And the master's on.

05:37.254 --> 05:39.089
♪ ♪

05:39.089 --> 05:40.674
- Casey did amazing
in the first round,

05:40.674 --> 05:43.510
set us up real good,
got us a good handle on.

05:43.510 --> 05:45.136
He did great.

05:45.136 --> 05:48.056
- Okay, power hammer's
almost clear. Go.

05:48.056 --> 05:50.600
- I'll go ahead and draw it
out and get a point on it

05:50.600 --> 05:51.935
before I hand it
back off to him.

05:51.935 --> 05:54.145
♪ ♪

05:54.145 --> 05:56.106
- I think one of our
biggest advantages will be,

05:56.106 --> 05:58.191
we have fun no matter what.

05:58.191 --> 06:00.235
It doesn't matter
if we're messing something up,

06:00.235 --> 06:01.820
or building the most beautiful
blade you've ever seen,

06:01.820 --> 06:03.488
we have fun either way.

06:03.488 --> 06:06.199
No one else has a point.
- They don't?

06:06.199 --> 06:08.034
Well, they better
put one on there.

06:08.034 --> 06:09.870
- That's the "point"
of the show.

06:09.870 --> 06:11.288
Ha-ha.

06:11.288 --> 06:12.747
- Kelly.

06:12.747 --> 06:15.000
Kelly... Kelly!
- Yeah!

06:15.000 --> 06:17.252
- Kelly got us
pretty well sorted out.

06:17.252 --> 06:20.839
Now it's my job to do something
about these finger holes...

06:20.839 --> 06:22.507
Right there?
- Yeah.

06:22.507 --> 06:23.508
- Because I'm not
real sure about them.

06:23.508 --> 06:25.302
I've never made any.

06:25.302 --> 06:26.845
- All we have to do
is have the holes big enough

06:26.845 --> 06:28.805
so we can get our
fingers through, though.

06:28.805 --> 06:30.390
- We need to get their freaking
big old fingers through.

06:30.390 --> 06:32.350
The approach
for the finger holes,

06:32.350 --> 06:34.185
I'm gonna just
drift them in...

06:34.185 --> 06:35.854
Whoo! Yes, ma'am.

06:35.854 --> 06:37.856
Yeah, I got your back.

06:37.856 --> 06:41.026
And then, we'll file them
and grind them into shape.

06:41.026 --> 06:42.611
- Nice!

06:42.611 --> 06:44.279
- Look at Raleigh hammer.

06:44.279 --> 06:46.197
We got a farrier
with a vengeance.

06:46.197 --> 06:48.074
- I just wanted
to hit something!

06:48.074 --> 06:49.993
- Switch!

06:49.993 --> 06:51.786
You have just
three hours remaining

06:51.786 --> 06:53.330
to finish your work!

06:53.330 --> 06:55.248
- Good luck.

06:55.248 --> 06:57.167
- That's too far in, I think,
'cause that steel

06:57.167 --> 06:59.502
is gonna want to
get stretched out.

06:59.502 --> 07:02.631
- We start out by punching
prick marks in our handle

07:02.631 --> 07:05.175
for our knuckle spacing.
- How does that look?

07:05.175 --> 07:07.594
- I don't know,
I've never made one.

07:07.594 --> 07:09.804
You can almost break your
knuckle on a knife like this,

07:09.804 --> 07:11.765
if your holes don't line up.

07:11.765 --> 07:13.558
- Knuckle dusters
have a curve to it.

07:13.558 --> 07:16.311
Those finger holes have to
be in an arc fashion.

07:16.311 --> 07:18.563
Otherwise,
it's gonna open your hand.

07:18.563 --> 07:20.440
Cutting with that
is gonna be a problem.

07:20.440 --> 07:22.651
- Easy, easy!

07:22.651 --> 07:23.860
If there aren't four holes
to where it's comfortable,

07:23.860 --> 07:25.528
I mean, if they're too small,

07:25.528 --> 07:26.655
and the judge
can't get his hands in,

07:26.655 --> 07:27.947
they'll send us home.

07:27.947 --> 07:29.240
- Switch!

07:29.240 --> 07:30.909
♪ ♪

07:30.909 --> 07:33.078
- That was very nicely set up.

07:33.078 --> 07:35.789
Thank you so much.
- Anytime, chum.

07:35.789 --> 07:38.291
- Jessica, she's my left
and my right arm.

07:38.291 --> 07:41.544
I joke that she's my Alfred,
and I'm Batman,

07:41.544 --> 07:43.672
so I get to run around
in the rubber outfit

07:43.672 --> 07:45.799
and underpants on the outside,

07:45.799 --> 07:47.175
and she keeps
everything together

07:47.175 --> 07:49.636
and makes sure it flows.

07:49.636 --> 07:52.138
- Both our apprentices
and our masters

07:52.138 --> 07:54.849
have had two turns each
at the anvil,

07:54.849 --> 07:56.393
and there's only one team

07:56.393 --> 08:00.105
that has yet to drift
any finger holes.

08:00.105 --> 08:01.398
- Our plan right now
for our finger holes

08:01.398 --> 08:03.525
is to use this piece of steel.

08:03.525 --> 08:05.443
We're gonna give it little
M shapes, as it goes through,

08:05.443 --> 08:07.153
and it's gonna be
half of our handguard.

08:07.153 --> 08:08.655
The other half of
the holes inside here

08:08.655 --> 08:10.407
are gonna be ground in
for the hand.

08:10.407 --> 08:12.075
So it's a two-piece connection

08:12.075 --> 08:13.785
that we're gonna
weld together.

08:13.785 --> 08:16.287
- All I'm thinking is,
"Show me an M."

08:16.287 --> 08:18.123
I just need to see an M.

08:18.123 --> 08:19.708
I wanna see that
if I get to this right now,

08:19.708 --> 08:21.710
that I have loops to
weld to a handle.

08:21.710 --> 08:23.461
Oh, that's interesting.

08:23.461 --> 08:24.796
To open up their holes,
they're using the horn...

08:24.796 --> 08:26.756
- Yeah.
- And a pike. Like it.

08:26.756 --> 08:28.675
- Yeah, they're drifting
their holes just like they are.

08:28.675 --> 08:30.427
They're drifting holes too.

08:30.427 --> 08:31.636
We're the only ones
that it's gonna weld.

08:31.636 --> 08:33.388
- How does it make you feel?

08:33.388 --> 08:34.931
- Makes me feel
freaking amazing.

08:34.931 --> 08:36.516
- Just--I just wanna see the M.

08:36.516 --> 08:38.435
[chuckles]
Show me an M.

08:38.435 --> 08:39.894
- Switch!

08:39.894 --> 08:42.230
Half your time
has already elapsed!

08:42.230 --> 08:44.858
- Make sure you got it
real secure in there, Kel.

08:44.858 --> 08:46.317
Start grinding that [bleep].

08:46.317 --> 08:47.694
- Ooh-ah,
she's already on to grinding.

08:47.694 --> 08:51.406
♪ ♪

08:51.406 --> 08:53.158
- I need a Band-Aid.

08:53.158 --> 08:54.451
- You okay?
- Yep, I'm good.

08:54.451 --> 08:55.744
I just need a Band-Aid.

08:55.744 --> 08:58.997
- Uh-oh.
- Oh...

08:58.997 --> 09:00.540
- That's a lot of blood.

09:00.540 --> 09:02.667
- It's not a cut.
It's a tear.

09:02.667 --> 09:04.169
- We've got the medic
coming in.

09:04.169 --> 09:05.879
- It's good.
No, no, I don't have time.

09:05.879 --> 09:08.214
No, no, it's not blood.
No. Please, no.

09:08.214 --> 09:10.550
I get a cut worse than this
every single day.

09:10.550 --> 09:12.010
It was way too far from
my heart to kill me.

09:12.010 --> 09:13.887
I just need to keep working.

09:13.887 --> 09:15.946
I don't have time.
I don't have time for this.

09:18.805 --> 09:19.716
You okay?
- Yep, I'm good.

09:19.716 --> 09:21.092
I just need a Band-Aid.

09:21.092 --> 09:23.636
- Uh-oh.
- Oh...

09:23.636 --> 09:25.221
- That's a lot of blood.
- No, no, I don't have time.

09:25.221 --> 09:27.724
No, no, it's not blood.
No. Please, no.

09:27.724 --> 09:30.268
The grinder attacked me.
[laughs]

09:30.268 --> 09:32.103
- [laughs]

09:32.103 --> 09:33.646
- Just give me
a Band-Aid right there.

09:33.646 --> 09:35.857
That's all I need.
It's not bad.

09:35.857 --> 09:37.233
- Kelly over there,
it look likes

09:37.233 --> 09:39.110
she messed up her finger
pretty bad.

09:39.110 --> 09:40.820
- And she's still
trying to work.

09:40.820 --> 09:42.488
- I don't wanna
leave the floor.

09:42.488 --> 09:44.032
It was just
a little bloody cut.

09:44.032 --> 09:45.742
I broke my foot in four places

09:45.742 --> 09:47.202
and shod ten horses
afterward.

09:47.202 --> 09:48.578
I just need to keep working.

09:48.578 --> 09:50.288
♪ ♪

09:50.288 --> 09:51.873
I don't have time.
I don't have time for this.

09:51.873 --> 09:54.209
- All right.
- Thanks.

09:54.209 --> 09:56.294
- Yeah, it'll be all right.

09:56.294 --> 09:57.921
- We don't even think about it
when the other one's bleeding.

09:57.921 --> 09:59.756
I'm like, she's gotta
keep working through it.

09:59.756 --> 10:01.549
That's what we do
for each other.

10:01.549 --> 10:02.884
Yeah, we don't worry about

10:02.884 --> 10:04.052
little flesh wounds
around here.

10:04.052 --> 10:06.596
It's all good.
- Switch!

10:06.596 --> 10:08.848
- Kelly,
we better [bleep] hope

10:08.848 --> 10:11.601
that we can rasp this.
We should've checked.

10:11.601 --> 10:13.478
I'm grinding on this blade,

10:13.478 --> 10:15.521
and all of a sudden,
I start thinking,

10:15.521 --> 10:17.523
"This blade's pretty hard."
We might be in trouble,

10:17.523 --> 10:21.569
because I'm not sure
our plan to rasp out

10:21.569 --> 10:25.156
these holes is gonna go
as easily as planned.

10:25.156 --> 10:26.991
Ah, I should've
punched them bigger.

10:26.991 --> 10:29.410
- We underestimated
the work hardness of a W1.

10:29.410 --> 10:31.371
Hand rasping's not easy.

10:31.371 --> 10:33.373
- If we don't get these
finger holes sorted out,

10:33.373 --> 10:35.416
so that the judges
can fit their fingers in,

10:35.416 --> 10:36.876
we're gonna have a problem.

10:36.876 --> 10:38.962
- Switch!

10:38.962 --> 10:40.463
- Our plan was to make a guard

10:40.463 --> 10:42.840
in an M shape like this.
Show me the M!

10:42.840 --> 10:44.634
Um, the steel
wasn't moving at all...

10:44.634 --> 10:45.885
- At all.
- When it does move,

10:45.885 --> 10:47.470
it's in giant arcs.

10:47.470 --> 10:49.305
- Trying to get
this piece of steel

10:49.305 --> 10:51.891
to move into the M shape
that we just--

10:51.891 --> 10:54.477
for the last three
revolutions of our turns,

10:54.477 --> 10:56.396
we just cannot get into shape.

10:56.396 --> 10:58.273
♪ ♪

10:58.273 --> 11:00.441
Grind it. [bleep] it.
Grind it. Flatten that out.

11:00.441 --> 11:02.485
Grind all four holes.
We don't have time.

11:02.485 --> 11:04.696
- They just took all the bend
out of it they put in it.

11:04.696 --> 11:06.990
- So I'm looking at the clock.
I'm freaking out.

11:06.990 --> 11:08.408
We don't have a handle.

11:08.408 --> 11:10.243
Yeah, grind it!
[blade whirs]

11:10.243 --> 11:13.538
We want four channels!
One, two, three, four, boom.

11:13.538 --> 11:15.331
- And he is now
grinding into his handle.

11:15.331 --> 11:17.417
- They've come up with an idea.

11:17.417 --> 11:19.794
Now, if they were to grind
the loops into that billet,

11:19.794 --> 11:21.296
they could just
weld those across.

11:21.296 --> 11:22.797
That would really
look like hell,

11:22.797 --> 11:24.007
but that could work.

11:24.007 --> 11:25.049
♪ ♪

11:25.049 --> 11:26.926
- Switch!

11:26.926 --> 11:29.304
There are only 30 minutes
remaining in this round!

11:29.304 --> 11:32.140
♪ ♪

11:32.140 --> 11:34.350
- There we go.
- Oh! Quenched.

11:34.350 --> 11:36.686
- Mark just quenched.

11:36.686 --> 11:38.396
- Ran my file down it.

11:38.396 --> 11:40.106
There is that little moment

11:40.106 --> 11:43.151
where I feel my stomach
coming up.

11:43.151 --> 11:45.028
- It's hard,
but it's not that hard.

11:45.028 --> 11:46.904
- Yeah,
that's what I'm feeling.

11:46.904 --> 11:49.032
I'm going for one more.

11:49.032 --> 11:51.451
All I can do is
take another quench,

11:51.451 --> 11:53.828
see how it comes out.

11:53.828 --> 11:55.872
- Use the small contact wheel.

11:55.872 --> 11:58.166
- I'm looking at the clock.
I've got 30 minutes.

11:58.166 --> 12:00.168
I don't have time
to [bleep] around anymore.

12:00.168 --> 12:01.669
I cannot teach Leon
anything else.

12:01.669 --> 12:04.088
I have to focus
on this blade right now.

12:04.088 --> 12:05.798
Otherwise,
we aren't gonna make it.

12:05.798 --> 12:07.967
[bleep] it, we're welding now.

12:07.967 --> 12:09.594
We just gotta get it to work.

12:09.594 --> 12:11.387
Just weld it to it
until it's done.

12:11.387 --> 12:13.056
That's the only thing
on my mind,

12:13.056 --> 12:14.265
just get something
to the judges.

12:14.265 --> 12:20.229
♪ ♪

12:20.229 --> 12:21.939
- Joe and Casey
are in the quench.

12:21.939 --> 12:23.483
- The blade is quenched...

12:23.483 --> 12:25.818
Sounds hard.
- Sounds hard to me.

12:25.818 --> 12:27.653
- We're letting it come to
temperature in the oil.

12:27.653 --> 12:29.322
♪ ♪

12:29.322 --> 12:31.324
- There you go, my friend.

12:31.324 --> 12:33.076
- [chuckles] What?

12:33.076 --> 12:35.453
- Oh, you knuckleheads!
- Oh, no way.

12:35.453 --> 12:38.039
- Finally somebody
brings a snack.

12:38.039 --> 12:41.459
- Joe snuck marshmallows
all the way here from Wyoming,

12:41.459 --> 12:43.336
and guess what...

12:43.336 --> 12:44.629
it will toast.

12:44.629 --> 12:48.508
♪ ♪

12:48.508 --> 12:50.134
- Tyler has quenched.

12:50.134 --> 12:51.511
Here we go.

12:51.511 --> 12:53.721
Five, four,

12:53.721 --> 12:56.641
three, two, one!

12:56.641 --> 12:58.059
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

12:58.059 --> 12:59.977
drop your tools!

12:59.977 --> 13:03.147
This first round of
competition is over!

13:03.147 --> 13:04.649
- That was fun.

13:04.649 --> 13:06.025
- We're hoping
for somebody else

13:06.025 --> 13:07.693
to have messed up
finger holes too.

13:07.693 --> 13:09.153
That's what we want.
- [chuckles]

13:09.153 --> 13:10.822
- We're wishing bad crap
on other people.

13:10.822 --> 13:12.490
- Bad karma, sorry.
- Sorry, guys.

13:12.490 --> 13:14.033
- We can make those
look really pretty

13:14.033 --> 13:15.284
with a little extra time.
- Yeah.

13:15.284 --> 13:16.786
- I don't think it said that

13:16.786 --> 13:18.371
the holes had
to be pretty yet.

13:18.371 --> 13:20.039
- No, there was nothing
in the rules about--

13:20.039 --> 13:20.998
- It had to be hard.
That was--it had to be hard.

13:20.998 --> 13:23.000
- Exactly.

13:23.000 --> 13:24.919
- Masters and apprentices,

13:24.919 --> 13:27.505
it's time for the judges
to take a look at your work.

13:27.505 --> 13:31.342
Raleigh, Kelly, please present
your blade to the judges.

13:31.342 --> 13:32.927
♪ ♪

13:32.927 --> 13:34.679
- That's a heck of a knife.

13:34.679 --> 13:36.139
I don't see
any kind of cracking

13:36.139 --> 13:38.266
or problems
with the steel itself.

13:38.266 --> 13:42.270
But the big thing is
these holes are pretty small.

13:42.270 --> 13:45.606
I'd really like to see these
holes opened up a little bit.

13:45.606 --> 13:47.817
- No one swings hammers
like farriers do,

13:47.817 --> 13:50.736
but remember, one of
these tests is a stab test,

13:50.736 --> 13:53.865
and it's a very wide point
for a stab.

13:53.865 --> 13:56.242
- Joe, Casey,
your team's up next.

13:56.242 --> 13:58.035
♪ ♪

13:58.035 --> 13:59.412
- Man,
that's an aggressive design.

13:59.412 --> 14:01.289
It's just really intimidating.

14:01.289 --> 14:02.999
Designed for cutting
marshmallows.

14:02.999 --> 14:04.917
[light laughter]

14:04.917 --> 14:07.170
I put this in my hand,
it's not comfortable yet,

14:07.170 --> 14:08.713
but I can see it getting there

14:08.713 --> 14:10.381
once this webbing's
taken care of.

14:10.381 --> 14:12.175
All in all,
I think you did a great job.

14:12.175 --> 14:13.885
Well done.

14:13.885 --> 14:16.596
- Tyler and Leon,
you guys are up next.

14:16.596 --> 14:19.432
- In a competition
where the defining part

14:19.432 --> 14:23.394
of this design
is all about the handle,

14:23.394 --> 14:25.062
it's unfinished,
and I can't even get my fingers

14:25.062 --> 14:26.856
to make it workable
at this stage,

14:26.856 --> 14:28.482
and that's very important

14:28.482 --> 14:30.985
when we're talking about
the trench knife.

14:30.985 --> 14:33.613
- Mark, Jessica,
you're up next.

14:33.613 --> 14:35.406
♪ ♪

14:35.406 --> 14:37.366
- It was a pleasure
to watch you guys work.

14:37.366 --> 14:39.410
The shape of this
is phenomenal.

14:39.410 --> 14:41.454
It's got an aggressive point
for stabbing.

14:41.454 --> 14:43.331
Your finger holes

14:43.331 --> 14:45.416
are comfortable
and well placed.

14:45.416 --> 14:47.418
But, uh...

14:47.418 --> 14:49.128
there's a crack.

14:49.128 --> 14:51.297
You can see it here,

14:51.297 --> 14:53.549
and you can also see it
on the other side.

14:53.549 --> 14:55.927
It's an unfortunate thing.

14:55.927 --> 14:58.971
- All right, bladesmiths,
while we go into deliberation,

14:58.971 --> 15:00.890
I'm gonna have you lay
your blades here on this table

15:00.890 --> 15:02.266
and step back
towards your anvils.

15:02.266 --> 15:05.728
♪ ♪

15:05.728 --> 15:07.438
- When they said
it was cracked,

15:07.438 --> 15:09.190
I was like, "Shoot,
they had the nicest blade."

15:09.190 --> 15:10.942
My heart fell for you.

15:10.942 --> 15:12.818
- I can't even figure out
where it came in.

15:12.818 --> 15:14.528
- All right, judges,
it's time to discuss

15:14.528 --> 15:16.572
who's going home
and who gets to stay.

15:16.572 --> 15:18.616
- In my mind,
certainly Raleigh and Kelly

15:18.616 --> 15:20.576
and Joe and Casey.

15:20.576 --> 15:22.036
These guys are moving forward,
without a doubt.

15:22.036 --> 15:24.664
And then,
it's between Tyler and Leon

15:24.664 --> 15:26.415
and Mark and Jessica.

15:26.415 --> 15:28.292
- We're gonna start
with Tyler and Leon.

15:28.292 --> 15:30.836
- [sighs]

15:30.836 --> 15:33.839
- I just don't see four hours
of work on this blade.

15:33.839 --> 15:36.968
It just--it's not as refined
as a lot of the other ones.

15:36.968 --> 15:40.012
I can't get a fingertip
into this hole.

15:40.012 --> 15:42.265
This is very square.

15:42.265 --> 15:44.475
In a knuckle duster, you'd like
to see some curvature to it,

15:44.475 --> 15:46.477
and this is just not that.

15:46.477 --> 15:49.063
- I like the fact
that they came up with

15:49.063 --> 15:53.109
another idea for achieving
what we wanted,

15:53.109 --> 15:55.319
but they didn't really have
a plan on how to finish it,

15:55.319 --> 15:57.238
and that shows.

15:57.238 --> 15:59.490
The fact that this blade
is a half-inch thick almost,

15:59.490 --> 16:02.326
and there's no definition
in the spine whatsoever.

16:02.326 --> 16:04.453
I seriously have doubts
on whether or not

16:04.453 --> 16:05.997
they're going to have
enough time in round two

16:05.997 --> 16:08.040
to do the things
they need to do

16:08.040 --> 16:09.834
to take care of their blade.

16:09.834 --> 16:11.460
- All right, let's move on
to Mark and Jessica.

16:11.460 --> 16:13.337
♪ ♪

16:13.337 --> 16:15.298
- First off,
it's a gorgeous knife,

16:15.298 --> 16:17.591
but the big thing for me is,
there are cracks.

16:17.591 --> 16:20.219
I mean, there's a crack here.
It follows through to here.

16:20.219 --> 16:22.388
- We've talked about this
on cracked knives before,

16:22.388 --> 16:24.265
what's called a bell stop,

16:24.265 --> 16:25.975
where you put a hole
at either end of that crack,

16:25.975 --> 16:27.893
so it can't travel anywhere.
- Right.

16:27.893 --> 16:30.896
- The question is,
will they know how to fix it?

16:30.896 --> 16:32.606
- Doug, have you made
your final decision?

16:32.606 --> 16:33.858
- Yes, I have.
- Dave, you've made yours?

16:33.858 --> 16:35.234
- Yes, I have.
- Ben?

16:35.234 --> 16:36.360
- Yeah.
- All right.

16:36.360 --> 16:39.155
Let's go tell our smiths.

16:39.155 --> 16:42.575
Bladesmiths, our judges have
completed their deliberation.

16:42.575 --> 16:45.494
It's time for one of you teams
to leave The Forge.

16:45.494 --> 16:49.725
♪ ♪

16:53.121 --> 16:55.233
It's time for one of
you teams to leave The Forge.

16:55.233 --> 16:56.943
♪ ♪

16:56.943 --> 16:58.528
Leon and Tyler.

16:58.528 --> 17:01.155
Your blade did not
make the cut.

17:01.155 --> 17:03.199
- Tyler, Leon,
I really appreciate the fact

17:03.199 --> 17:05.702
that you guys came up with
a complete different direction

17:05.702 --> 17:07.787
for putting those holes,

17:07.787 --> 17:10.248
but in the execution,
you just ran out of time.

17:10.248 --> 17:13.042
At the end, your knife
just isn't nearly as finished

17:13.042 --> 17:14.669
as any of our others,

17:14.669 --> 17:16.421
and that's why
we're letting you go.

17:16.421 --> 17:20.258
- Tyler, Leon, please,
surrender your weapon.

17:20.258 --> 17:22.343
- This is my first time
using a power hammer,

17:22.343 --> 17:25.054
so the fact that
I was able to give Iron Man

17:25.054 --> 17:27.807
an actual nice piece
of steel to work with,

17:27.807 --> 17:29.475
I was very happy.

17:29.475 --> 17:31.060
- This is his sixth knife,

17:31.060 --> 17:34.022
and he did it
in front of the whole world.

17:34.022 --> 17:36.274
I'm extremely proud of Leon.

17:36.274 --> 17:38.776
♪ ♪

17:38.776 --> 17:40.695
- Congratulations,
bladesmiths,

17:40.695 --> 17:42.363
you've made it to
the second round.

17:42.363 --> 17:43.990
And now that your blades
have been tempered,

17:43.990 --> 17:45.533
it's time to turn them into

17:45.533 --> 17:47.285
fully functional
combat trench knifes,

17:47.285 --> 17:49.245
by attaching
handle scales to them,

17:49.245 --> 17:52.707
using the range of materials
provided in our pantry.

17:52.707 --> 17:55.752
You will have three hours
in which to complete your work.

17:55.752 --> 17:58.838
Now, I remind you that you will
work in 30 minute intervals,

17:58.838 --> 18:00.798
apprentices starting first.

18:00.798 --> 18:03.009
After this round's time is up,

18:03.009 --> 18:05.553
your blades will be tested
for strength and durability

18:05.553 --> 18:07.263
in a fuel can stab,

18:07.263 --> 18:10.349
and for sharpness
in a fire hose slice.

18:10.349 --> 18:11.726
Good luck.

18:11.726 --> 18:14.145
Your time starts... now.

18:14.145 --> 18:16.981
♪ ♪

18:16.981 --> 18:19.192
- If you drill out
there and there,

18:19.192 --> 18:21.903
I think that's gonna help
a lot of our problems.

18:21.903 --> 18:24.530
Our biggest challenge
this round is

18:24.530 --> 18:26.365
to fix our freaking messed up
finger holes, man.

18:26.365 --> 18:28.409
- Yeah.

18:28.409 --> 18:30.036
- There's nothing worse than
having your fingers spread out

18:30.036 --> 18:32.121
on something that you're
trying to use as a weapon.

18:32.121 --> 18:34.207
- Right.
Can injure the user.

18:34.207 --> 18:36.042
♪ ♪

18:36.042 --> 18:38.878
- If you've got a crack,
you don't fix it.

18:38.878 --> 18:40.880
both: Throw it away.
- Start again.

18:40.880 --> 18:43.800
♪ ♪

18:43.800 --> 18:46.469
Once we've got
the handle figured out.

18:46.469 --> 18:48.638
- First, I'm going to

18:48.638 --> 18:50.765
widen those finger loops.

18:50.765 --> 18:53.434
- My instruction to Jess is,

18:53.434 --> 18:55.686
make it feel like
a kit glove.

18:55.686 --> 18:58.523
Bring that one in a little bit.
That's gonna help.

18:58.523 --> 19:00.691
Jess's hands are smaller.

19:00.691 --> 19:02.777
She's gonna be more aware
of that pinching

19:02.777 --> 19:04.946
between the fingers,

19:04.946 --> 19:06.572
which is kind of a good thing
in some ways.

19:06.572 --> 19:10.451
♪ ♪

19:10.451 --> 19:11.869
- I'm putting
a skull crusher in,

19:11.869 --> 19:14.580
because Doug thinks it'll kill.

19:14.580 --> 19:16.666
No one had one,
so I thought,

19:16.666 --> 19:18.626
"We have enough meat there.

19:18.626 --> 19:21.337
Why not add one,
give it a little extra flair?"

19:21.337 --> 19:23.548
If I had to pick a knife
to bring to a gun fight...

19:23.548 --> 19:25.883
- This one wouldn't be
a bad choice.

19:25.883 --> 19:28.636
- Switch!
- Oh, that's ebony.

19:28.636 --> 19:30.555
First thing I do when I take
the blade back from Casey

19:30.555 --> 19:33.057
is start setting up
for the handle.

19:33.057 --> 19:35.476
- We noticed a piece of
white paper Micarta.

19:35.476 --> 19:37.562
- It'll be a good strong
handle material.

19:37.562 --> 19:39.981
♪ ♪

19:39.981 --> 19:42.483
- We're still struggling
with the holes.

19:42.483 --> 19:44.235
There comes a point where
you gotta just do your best,

19:44.235 --> 19:46.320
and you've gotta move on
to the next thing...

19:46.320 --> 19:47.947
Still gotta get
the handle on it.

19:47.947 --> 19:49.615
So that's what
we're going after now.

19:49.615 --> 19:51.242
- Switch!

19:51.242 --> 19:52.952
- Raleigh, I need a decision--

19:52.952 --> 19:54.162
- What?
I don't [bleep] care, dude.

19:54.162 --> 19:55.746
Just grab that.

19:55.746 --> 19:57.498
- Seems very brittle.

19:57.498 --> 19:59.125
- It's fine. I just wanna
get a handle on there.

19:59.125 --> 20:01.711
♪ ♪

20:01.711 --> 20:03.838
- Lovely. Nice job.

20:03.838 --> 20:06.132
We know we've got
the weird finger loops done.

20:06.132 --> 20:09.010
- And now I just focus
all of my thought

20:09.010 --> 20:10.803
on getting that handle shaped.

20:10.803 --> 20:13.681
- So, I want you
to consider that as a circle.

20:13.681 --> 20:16.475
There we go. And come all
the way out to the far edge.

20:16.475 --> 20:18.895
- I'm really impressed
with this relationship.

20:18.895 --> 20:22.440
It is a true form of
master and apprentice.

20:22.440 --> 20:25.151
Switch!

20:25.151 --> 20:27.695
- Now we've gotta figure out
what to do about that crack.

20:27.695 --> 20:29.655
It's a huge problem.

20:29.655 --> 20:32.325
- They're seeing if they can
grind out the cracks.

20:32.325 --> 20:33.659
- You add heat to that thing,

20:33.659 --> 20:37.079
and that crack
is going to enlarge.

20:37.079 --> 20:38.664
- Seeing some headshaking
from Mark over there...

20:38.664 --> 20:40.499
- Oh, yeah.

20:40.499 --> 20:42.293
- It's as good
as I'm gonna get it.

20:42.293 --> 20:43.628
I'm not gonna even deal
with those cracks.

20:43.628 --> 20:45.588
There's no point in it.

20:45.588 --> 20:48.257
- I wanna get this thing glued
sooner than later.

20:48.257 --> 20:50.301
- It's been taking Raleigh
a bit of time

20:50.301 --> 20:52.470
to get this handle together.

20:52.470 --> 20:53.888
- We're having
a hard time recovering

20:53.888 --> 20:55.556
from our finger holes.

20:55.556 --> 20:58.100
Our handle looks like bad poo,

20:58.100 --> 21:00.895
but part of competing is
you just gotta take your lumps,

21:00.895 --> 21:02.980
and you gotta
go on with things.

21:02.980 --> 21:05.441
- Switch!

21:05.441 --> 21:09.070
- The other day, Casey made
his first large knife.

21:09.070 --> 21:11.030
There's a whole new skill set
to learn there.

21:11.030 --> 21:12.949
- How fast do you run
one of these?

21:12.949 --> 21:15.493
- And now,
we need to grind the bevels.

21:15.493 --> 21:17.203
Here's your chance.
Get to practicing.

21:17.203 --> 21:18.913
♪ ♪

21:18.913 --> 21:21.457
Take your time. Chill out.

21:21.457 --> 21:23.209
- May not be the most
opportune time

21:23.209 --> 21:26.170
to practice a skill
you just learned a week ago,

21:26.170 --> 21:28.339
but no time like the present,

21:28.339 --> 21:30.258
so I hopped on that
belt sander and gave her hell.

21:30.258 --> 21:33.219
- [chuckles]
That's gorgeous.

21:33.219 --> 21:36.222
- You have only half an hour
left in this competition.

21:36.222 --> 21:40.226
Masters, you're batting
cleanup, so make it count.

21:40.226 --> 21:43.646
- Right now, we just have to
make a beautiful thing.

21:43.646 --> 21:45.940
Let's put a fantastic
handle on it.

21:45.940 --> 21:49.527
- I think Jessica
is glad to be done

21:49.527 --> 21:51.737
with the working portion
of this for her.

21:51.737 --> 21:53.823
Now she's just gotta
cheerlead her master,

21:53.823 --> 21:56.409
and wait and see what happens.

21:56.409 --> 21:58.202
- We've just got to make
a beautiful knife,

21:58.202 --> 21:59.912
put it in the hands
of the gods.

21:59.912 --> 22:02.123
- Yeah.

22:02.123 --> 22:05.251
- I know the finger holes
weren't finished,

22:05.251 --> 22:06.711
but I see that hamon
in the blade,

22:06.711 --> 22:09.088
and nothing brings
that kinda stuff out

22:09.088 --> 22:11.132
like a hand-sanded finish.

22:11.132 --> 22:12.508
- That doesn't look like
a whole lot of fun right there.

22:12.508 --> 22:13.884
- You just wait
and see what it does.

22:13.884 --> 22:15.052
- I'm sure it's gonna be
beautiful.

22:15.052 --> 22:16.971
♪ ♪

22:16.971 --> 22:18.806
- Ten, nine,

22:18.806 --> 22:20.766
eight, seven,

22:20.766 --> 22:22.935
six, five,

22:22.935 --> 22:24.729
four, three,

22:24.729 --> 22:27.106
two, one!

22:27.106 --> 22:30.151
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.
Stop what you're doing.

22:30.151 --> 22:32.403
This second round of
competition is over.

22:32.403 --> 22:34.405
♪ ♪

22:34.405 --> 22:37.908
- I'm trying to ignore the fact
that there are cracks,

22:37.908 --> 22:39.952
but damn, she looks good.

22:39.952 --> 22:42.371
- Bladesmiths,
this is the strength test,

22:42.371 --> 22:43.914
the fuel can stab.

22:43.914 --> 22:45.541
I'm gonna use your knives

22:45.541 --> 22:49.170
to stab holes
in these fuel cans five times.

22:49.170 --> 22:51.005
Remember, it's not what your
knives do to the fuel cans,

22:51.005 --> 22:54.091
but what the fuel cans
do to your knives.

22:54.091 --> 22:55.551
Raleigh, Kelly, you're up
first. Are you ready?

22:55.551 --> 22:57.511
- Yes.
- Yes, sir.

22:57.511 --> 22:59.638
- We're really excited
for the toughness test.

22:59.638 --> 23:01.349
We fixed that point on it.
It's definitely stabbier.

23:01.349 --> 23:03.434
And we're really excited
to see what's gonna happen.

23:03.434 --> 23:10.399
♪ ♪

23:13.319 --> 23:15.321
- [laughing]
- Hey...

23:15.321 --> 23:17.239
[laughter]

23:17.239 --> 23:19.283
♪ ♪

23:19.283 --> 23:21.577
- Raleigh, Kelly,
this is quite a knife.

23:21.577 --> 23:24.330
Got a nice point
for penetration.

23:24.330 --> 23:28.834
But there's some chipping here.

23:28.834 --> 23:31.212
The very point is still

23:31.212 --> 23:32.671
as sharp as it was
when you made it,

23:32.671 --> 23:34.173
but, uh, there's no denying

23:34.173 --> 23:36.133
there was a little chip
on the edge here.

23:36.133 --> 23:37.885
Joe, Casey, you guys are up.
Are you ready?

23:37.885 --> 23:39.595
- Oh, yeah.
- Let's do it.

23:39.595 --> 23:41.847
This is what
me and Joe live for,

23:41.847 --> 23:43.516
making knives and just
testing them to destruction.

23:43.516 --> 23:45.101
- What's the use
of making something

23:45.101 --> 23:46.811
if you can't find out
where its limits are?

23:46.811 --> 23:53.776
♪ ♪

24:00.908 --> 24:02.701
- Well, Joe, Casey,

24:02.701 --> 24:04.703
your edge held up perfectly,
but this handle...

24:04.703 --> 24:06.122
[chuckles] Hurts.

24:06.122 --> 24:07.832
What I ended up with
was a position

24:07.832 --> 24:10.543
that made my pinkie
take a lot of the force.

24:10.543 --> 24:12.878
The holes, it just needed
to be closer together

24:12.878 --> 24:14.380
and a little taller,

24:14.380 --> 24:16.549
but, uh, that edge,
it's perfect.

24:16.549 --> 24:17.967
- Thanks.
- Thank you.

24:17.967 --> 24:21.011
Mark, Jessica, you ready?
- Indeed.

24:21.011 --> 24:23.681
That chip on Raleigh
and Kelly's blade,

24:23.681 --> 24:26.350
it's making me think
heavily about ours.

24:26.350 --> 24:28.352
We know we've got
that cracking in there,

24:28.352 --> 24:30.396
something that
we did not address.

24:30.396 --> 24:34.358
- This could end up being
a beautiful paperweight

24:34.358 --> 24:36.902
that shatters on the floor.
- Several paperweights.

24:36.902 --> 24:39.071
It's to the gods now.

24:39.071 --> 24:44.593
♪ ♪

24:48.109 --> 24:49.736
Ben's ready
to test our blade.

24:49.736 --> 24:51.404
We know we've got
that cracking in there,

24:51.404 --> 24:53.281
something that
we did not address.

24:53.281 --> 24:55.158
It's to the gods now.

24:55.158 --> 25:01.957
♪ ♪

25:07.587 --> 25:09.297
Poked holes. [laughs]

25:09.297 --> 25:13.510
♪ ♪

25:13.510 --> 25:15.845
- [exhales]

25:15.845 --> 25:18.807
- Well, Mark, Jessica,
your edge held up beautifully.

25:18.807 --> 25:20.517
Those surface cracks
we saw in round one

25:20.517 --> 25:22.602
held together.
Well done on the handle.

25:22.602 --> 25:24.271
This is the only one
that I could get

25:24.271 --> 25:27.607
my hand all the way in
and hold it with strength,

25:27.607 --> 25:29.776
and it allowed me
to penetrate very deeply.

25:29.776 --> 25:31.152
Overall, very well done.

25:31.152 --> 25:33.280
That's quite a trench knife.

25:33.280 --> 25:34.906
- It didn't blow up.
- It didn't blow up at all.

25:34.906 --> 25:37.409
- It didn't blow up.
It's still one piece.

25:37.409 --> 25:38.994
- Up next is
the sharpness test,

25:38.994 --> 25:40.829
and for that,
I give you to Dave.

25:40.829 --> 25:42.205
♪ ♪

25:42.205 --> 25:44.291
[laughter]

25:44.291 --> 25:45.917
- All right, bladesmiths,

25:45.917 --> 25:48.044
to test the sharpness
of your blade,

25:48.044 --> 25:49.546
this is all about what your
blades do to these fire hoses.

25:49.546 --> 25:51.756
Raleigh, Kelly, you ready?
- Yes, sir.

25:51.756 --> 25:58.680
♪ ♪

26:00.974 --> 26:03.101
[both imitate explosion]

26:03.101 --> 26:05.061
♪ ♪

26:05.061 --> 26:07.355
- All right, Raleigh, Kelly,
you made a sharp knife.

26:07.355 --> 26:08.815
There was no resi--well,

26:08.815 --> 26:11.318
I can't say
there was no resistance

26:11.318 --> 26:13.194
by the mark on
my little finger right there.

26:13.194 --> 26:15.989
My little finger
is being pushed so far back

26:15.989 --> 26:17.782
by that webbing right there.

26:17.782 --> 26:20.201
If that were a little bit
further forward,

26:20.201 --> 26:23.955
it might actually be
almost comfortable.

26:23.955 --> 26:25.332
All right, Joe, Casey,
you're up. You ready?

26:25.332 --> 26:26.291
- Oh, yeah.
- Let's do it.

26:26.291 --> 26:27.375
- Okay.

26:27.375 --> 26:34.299
♪ ♪

26:35.592 --> 26:37.469
- Good job.
- Thanks.

26:37.469 --> 26:40.930
- Joe, Casey,
beautiful, sharp edge.

26:40.930 --> 26:42.807
I love the look of this,

26:42.807 --> 26:45.393
but that little finger
is murder.

26:45.393 --> 26:47.646
Man, I wish you had spent
a little bit more time

26:47.646 --> 26:49.022
grinding out that ring.

26:49.022 --> 26:50.899
♪ ♪

26:50.899 --> 26:52.817
All right, Mark, Jessica,
you ready?

26:52.817 --> 26:53.818
- Yes.
- Indeed.

26:53.818 --> 26:54.861
- Okay.

26:54.861 --> 27:01.326
♪ ♪

27:01.326 --> 27:03.411
- Ooh.
- [exhales]

27:03.411 --> 27:06.373
- That is... incredibly sharp.

27:06.373 --> 27:09.751
I actually was through the hose
before I realized I'd hit it.

27:09.751 --> 27:11.419
And those surface cracks
haven't opened up

27:11.419 --> 27:13.713
or affected the performance
of your blade at all.

27:13.713 --> 27:15.173
Let's get to your handle.

27:15.173 --> 27:17.384
I can adjust this
any way I want.

27:17.384 --> 27:18.510
The finger holes
are big enough.

27:18.510 --> 27:19.886
There's height in them.

27:19.886 --> 27:21.137
Good job.
- Thank you so much.

27:21.137 --> 27:22.764
- Thank you.

27:22.764 --> 27:24.182
♪ ♪

27:24.182 --> 27:25.934
- All right, bladesmiths,

27:25.934 --> 27:27.602
the judges have completed
their deliberation,

27:27.602 --> 27:29.562
and they've made
a final decision.

27:29.562 --> 27:32.399
It's time for one of
these teams to leave The Forge.

27:32.399 --> 27:34.484
The team leaving
The Forge is...

27:34.484 --> 27:38.029
♪ ♪

27:38.029 --> 27:39.906
Raleigh and Kelly.

27:39.906 --> 27:42.492
Your blade
did not make the cut.

27:42.492 --> 27:44.160
- Raleigh, Kelly,

27:44.160 --> 27:46.454
you guys brought
so much energy and fun.

27:46.454 --> 27:48.039
It's not an easy challenge.

27:48.039 --> 27:49.833
But at the end of the day,

27:49.833 --> 27:51.960
there's only one blade here
that hurt the user

27:51.960 --> 27:54.337
and took edge damage.

27:54.337 --> 27:57.298
It's for this reason
your team's going home.

27:57.298 --> 28:00.135
- Kelly, Raleigh,
please surrender your blade.

28:00.135 --> 28:01.219
♪ ♪

28:01.219 --> 28:03.096
- I don't like it.

28:03.096 --> 28:04.556
I don't like it when I don't
know how to do something.

28:04.556 --> 28:06.558
I'm going home.
I'm gonna make

28:06.558 --> 28:07.934
some of them trench knives,
and I'm gonna be,

28:07.934 --> 28:09.978
like, the queen
trench knife maker.

28:09.978 --> 28:12.063
What you think, Kel?

28:12.063 --> 28:14.691
- I think that I'm just gonna
work on regular knives.

28:14.691 --> 28:18.361
♪ ♪

28:18.361 --> 28:19.821
- All right, bladesmiths,

28:19.821 --> 28:21.322
you've made it into
the final round.

28:21.322 --> 28:23.700
However, your work
is not over yet.

28:23.700 --> 28:25.660
We're sending you back
to your home forges

28:25.660 --> 28:27.787
to re-create an iconic weapon
from history.

28:27.787 --> 28:29.164
That weapon is...

28:29.164 --> 28:31.416
♪ ♪

28:31.416 --> 28:32.917
The Chinese Dao.

28:32.917 --> 28:35.253
♪ ♪

28:35.253 --> 28:37.714
Referred to as "The Courage
of All Soldiers,"

28:37.714 --> 28:39.674
the Dao is one of
China's oldest

28:39.674 --> 28:41.676
and most revered
edged weapons.

28:41.676 --> 28:44.512
For over 3,000 years,
this single-edged sword

28:44.512 --> 28:46.764
was carried into war
by Chinese cavalry.

28:46.764 --> 28:48.933
The blade's slight curve
offered its user

28:48.933 --> 28:51.144
superior thrusting
and chopping power,

28:51.144 --> 28:53.396
while its concave guard
prevented enemy blood

28:53.396 --> 28:55.023
from dripping onto the handle.

28:55.023 --> 28:56.691
Mounted soldiers
favored the weapon

28:56.691 --> 28:58.485
for its ease of use
on horseback.

28:58.485 --> 29:00.320
Often wielded at a gallop,

29:00.320 --> 29:01.946
the sword could fatally
sever enemy limbs

29:01.946 --> 29:03.823
with little resistance.

29:03.823 --> 29:05.825
Today, the Dao's legacy
lives on through its use

29:05.825 --> 29:07.911
in martial art forms
like tai chi,

29:07.911 --> 29:11.498
and in Chinese films
like "Brotherhood of Blades."

29:11.498 --> 29:13.708
Your blade parameters
are as follows:

29:13.708 --> 29:15.126
The length of the blade

29:15.126 --> 29:17.545
must fall between
26 and 28 inches.

29:17.545 --> 29:21.257
Your handle must include
a ring pommel and guard.

29:21.257 --> 29:23.718
- I only ever forged two things
in the knife world

29:23.718 --> 29:26.554
that are above 24 inches.

29:26.554 --> 29:28.765
I just hope our skills
can pull us through.

29:28.765 --> 29:30.600
- You will have five days
at your home forge

29:30.600 --> 29:33.436
to accomplish this, but just
like rounds one and two,

29:33.436 --> 29:36.189
only one of you can work
at the anvil at a time.

29:36.189 --> 29:38.024
And you will rotate each day.

29:38.024 --> 29:40.193
After five days,
you will return

29:40.193 --> 29:43.321
and present your Chinese Daos
to our panel of expert judges,

29:43.321 --> 29:44.989
and only after they've
brutally tested them

29:44.989 --> 29:46.533
will they declare
one of your teams

29:46.533 --> 29:48.576
the "Forged in Fire" champions

29:48.576 --> 29:50.662
and hand you that check
for ten grand.

29:50.662 --> 29:52.163
Good luck, bladesmiths.

29:52.163 --> 29:53.873
We'll see you in five days.

29:53.873 --> 29:55.750
- Congratulations.

29:55.750 --> 29:58.336
♪ ♪

29:58.336 --> 29:59.754
- I've never used this one.

29:59.754 --> 30:01.673
♪ ♪

30:01.673 --> 30:03.758
- [chuckles]
[blade whirs]

30:03.758 --> 30:05.969
Casey's never forged
a blade this length,

30:05.969 --> 30:08.221
but, hey, just 'cause you've
never done something before

30:08.221 --> 30:10.265
doesn't mean you can't do it.

30:10.265 --> 30:12.642
- I'm really excited
to build this Chinese Dao.

30:12.642 --> 30:16.229
It's an oversized chopper with
an elegant, pretty handle.

30:16.229 --> 30:17.855
♪ ♪

30:17.855 --> 30:20.984
At our thickest point,
2 and an 8.

30:20.984 --> 30:22.944
- The challenging part
on this blade, I think,

30:22.944 --> 30:25.154
is gonna be the thinness of it,

30:25.154 --> 30:27.365
and getting the weight down
to where I feel

30:27.365 --> 30:29.784
the judges are gonna be
comfortable testing it.

30:29.784 --> 30:31.578
So, the game plan
is forge thick,

30:31.578 --> 30:33.162
and then we'll take
that meat out

30:33.162 --> 30:34.581
when it comes to grinding.

30:34.581 --> 30:36.291
- I like working by hand more.

30:36.291 --> 30:38.126
I feel like
I have more control.

30:38.126 --> 30:39.711
But the best thing
about the power hammer

30:39.711 --> 30:42.046
is that it saves time.

30:42.046 --> 30:43.631
- [bleep].
Now that's a problem.

30:43.631 --> 30:44.716
♪ ♪

30:44.716 --> 30:46.217
We busted that off.

30:46.217 --> 30:48.136
♪ ♪

30:48.136 --> 30:49.637
We've only got five hours
to work today,

30:49.637 --> 30:51.514
and the power hammer failing,

30:51.514 --> 30:54.142
that kind threw
a monkey wrench into it.

30:54.142 --> 30:58.521
♪ ♪

30:58.521 --> 31:02.317
- We've made it
to the final round,

31:02.317 --> 31:04.360
probably by the skin
of our teeth.

31:04.360 --> 31:06.321
[laughs]

31:06.321 --> 31:09.782
I've never made
a precision weapon

31:09.782 --> 31:11.242
like this before.

31:11.242 --> 31:12.994
- That's the scary part.
- Yeah.

31:12.994 --> 31:15.204
♪ ♪

31:15.204 --> 31:17.081
I'm going to do my best

31:17.081 --> 31:19.626
to forge out
the entire blade profile,

31:19.626 --> 31:22.211
so that Mark is
set up well for tomorrow

31:22.211 --> 31:23.838
going into quench.

31:23.838 --> 31:25.673
- This is strange for us,

31:25.673 --> 31:28.343
because I literally
can't do anything.

31:28.343 --> 31:33.556
♪ ♪

31:33.556 --> 31:35.600
- [groans, chuckles]

31:35.600 --> 31:37.018
Driving me nuts.

31:37.018 --> 31:39.103
This is the hardest days' work

31:39.103 --> 31:40.313
that I've ever had
in my life...

31:40.313 --> 31:42.398
- [chuckles]

31:42.398 --> 31:43.733
- And I haven't picked up
a ruddy hammer.

31:43.733 --> 31:44.984
- [chuckles]

31:44.984 --> 31:47.278
♪ ♪

31:47.278 --> 31:50.031
- Joe gave me a rundown on
how to fix the power hammer,

31:50.031 --> 31:52.367
instead of me pounding out
by hand, and I'm glad he did,

31:52.367 --> 31:54.369
because that was kind of
a stupid thought.

31:54.369 --> 31:56.287
I think I left Joe
in a pretty good spot.

31:56.287 --> 31:58.498
- We're going for the gorgeous

31:58.498 --> 32:01.209
girl-next-door look
with a touch of makeup on.

32:01.209 --> 32:02.502
- That's right.

32:02.502 --> 32:04.170
I'm very excited to see Joe

32:04.170 --> 32:06.255
take this blade
to the next level.

32:06.255 --> 32:08.007
I can't wait to see how
the quench is gonna turn out.

32:08.007 --> 32:09.676
- The quenching is
nerve-wracking.

32:09.676 --> 32:11.636
If you tilt it,
if you turn it,

32:11.636 --> 32:14.722
it can cause a blade that
normally wouldn't warp to warp.

32:14.722 --> 32:16.808
♪ ♪

32:16.808 --> 32:18.643
It looks absolutely gorgeous.

32:18.643 --> 32:20.895
♪ ♪

32:20.895 --> 32:22.730
Now I've gotta thin
the blade down quite a bit.

32:22.730 --> 32:25.441
It's supposed to be
nice and light.

32:25.441 --> 32:27.902
If I grind it too thin,
and the edge buckles

32:27.902 --> 32:29.904
the second
it hits something hard,

32:29.904 --> 32:31.989
then obviously, they'll like it
because it's light,

32:31.989 --> 32:34.784
and then they'll hate it
because the edge got deformed.

32:34.784 --> 32:37.203
So what I'm looking at
is a nice even balance here,

32:37.203 --> 32:38.830
so that this blade
will sail through

32:38.830 --> 32:40.832
whatever it is that
they put in front of it.

32:40.832 --> 32:42.291
What do you think, Casey?

32:42.291 --> 32:44.252
- Not bad for an amateur.
- Really?

32:44.252 --> 32:46.087
♪ ♪

32:46.087 --> 32:47.338
- Here we go.

32:47.338 --> 32:49.298
Finally in hand.
- Awesome.

32:49.298 --> 32:51.634
- Jessica's put me
in a fantastic place.

32:51.634 --> 32:54.762
Now I would like to get
working into the guard.

32:54.762 --> 32:56.681
♪ ♪

32:56.681 --> 32:58.641
I've got a belt buckle.

32:58.641 --> 33:00.643
I'd actually like
to use that as the guard,

33:00.643 --> 33:03.479
but turn the knot
inwards towards the blade

33:03.479 --> 33:05.314
so it's almost invisible.

33:05.314 --> 33:07.900
It'd be like one of
those little peek details.

33:07.900 --> 33:09.819
Now, time to quench.

33:09.819 --> 33:11.863
I've been quite nervous
about the quench.

33:11.863 --> 33:13.823
It's very thin.
And I'm just expecting

33:13.823 --> 33:16.242
this thing to turn into
a floppy noodle on me.

33:16.242 --> 33:17.785
It's now or never.

33:17.785 --> 33:19.662
♪ ♪

33:19.662 --> 33:21.456
This could all go
to hell right now.

33:21.456 --> 33:23.040
♪ ♪

33:23.040 --> 33:24.542
You're in the hands
of the gods.

33:24.542 --> 33:30.047
♪ ♪

33:30.047 --> 33:31.382
- Everything is
smooth sailing,

33:31.382 --> 33:33.676
and then a bomb is dropped.

33:33.676 --> 33:34.900
- [bleep].

33:39.402 --> 33:40.862
I've been quite nervous about the quench.

33:40.862 --> 33:42.614
It's very thin.
And I'm just expecting

33:42.614 --> 33:45.242
this thing to turn into
a floppy noodle on me.

33:45.242 --> 33:52.124
♪ ♪

33:54.793 --> 33:56.586
Put it between some wood,

33:56.586 --> 33:58.839
drop an anvil
on top of the wood.

33:58.839 --> 34:01.550
♪ ♪

34:01.550 --> 34:03.135
It's so straight.

34:03.135 --> 34:05.345
- [laughs] Yay.

34:05.345 --> 34:06.680
♪ ♪

34:06.680 --> 34:08.265
- There's my apprentice.

34:08.265 --> 34:09.891
- I think I left Joe
in a good spot.

34:09.891 --> 34:11.852
He got the guards
completely done.

34:11.852 --> 34:13.478
Handle scales, done.

34:13.478 --> 34:15.355
- I got a nice tight fit
up in here.

34:15.355 --> 34:17.232
Casey rocked the shop
yesterday,

34:17.232 --> 34:19.693
and I am excited
to start this final assembly,

34:19.693 --> 34:21.403
and make it look like a sword.

34:21.403 --> 34:23.280
♪ ♪

34:23.280 --> 34:24.990
- This is the job
of every good apprentice.

34:24.990 --> 34:26.783
You sit in the EasyChair,
eat Trail Mix.

34:26.783 --> 34:28.994
Isn't that
what we're supposed to do?

34:28.994 --> 34:32.247
- Casey wanted to inlay
pins in the ring,

34:32.247 --> 34:33.748
one for each of
the competitors,

34:33.748 --> 34:36.001
so we're gonna have two pins

34:36.001 --> 34:37.878
that hold the pommel
to the tang,

34:37.878 --> 34:40.505
and then six more pins
in the ring on the bottom.

34:40.505 --> 34:42.424
- I think it turned out
amazing.

34:42.424 --> 34:44.593
It's gonna slice and dice
anything they swing it at.

34:44.593 --> 34:45.886
♪ ♪

34:45.886 --> 34:48.013
- And there is no edge damage.

34:48.013 --> 34:50.015
♪ ♪

34:50.015 --> 34:52.809
- Today, I am pretty tired,

34:52.809 --> 34:54.686
but there's still
work to be done.

34:54.686 --> 34:57.772
I need to get the ring pommel
in the back.

34:57.772 --> 35:01.067
♪ ♪

35:01.067 --> 35:03.403
Turns out there was a gap.

35:03.403 --> 35:04.821
♪ ♪

35:04.821 --> 35:08.575
It's very, very stressful.

35:08.575 --> 35:10.911
- Okay...

35:10.911 --> 35:12.704
- If I can't get
this pommel fitted on,

35:12.704 --> 35:16.041
then... that $10,000,

35:16.041 --> 35:17.501
losing it could be my fault.

35:17.501 --> 35:22.047
♪ ♪

35:22.047 --> 35:24.424
- Bladesmiths,
welcome back to The Forge.

35:24.424 --> 35:26.051
You've had five days
at your home forges

35:26.051 --> 35:27.719
to work on your Chinese Dao.

35:27.719 --> 35:29.804
Joe, Casey,
tell us a little bit about

35:29.804 --> 35:32.057
how your blade is constructed.

35:32.057 --> 35:33.892
- Our blade's at a 51-60.

35:33.892 --> 35:36.186
We put a hidden tang
handle on it,

35:36.186 --> 35:39.773
and then a ring pommel
with eight brass pins in it.

35:39.773 --> 35:41.858
Smooth and easy.

35:41.858 --> 35:43.527
- All right, Mark, Jessica,
how'd it go for you all?

35:43.527 --> 35:45.362
- It was a little bit of
a mad scamper at the end,

35:45.362 --> 35:47.239
but it went pretty smoothly.

35:47.239 --> 35:49.282
It's a full-tang construction.

35:49.282 --> 35:51.117
And then we have
a small spacer

35:51.117 --> 35:53.203
and a threaded rod
holding the ring on.

35:53.203 --> 35:55.413
- All right.
Your weapons will now be put

35:55.413 --> 35:56.706
through a series
of three tests.

35:56.706 --> 35:58.250
Doug?

35:58.250 --> 36:00.585
- This is the kill test.

36:00.585 --> 36:03.004
To see what kinda lethal damage
your blade will do,

36:03.004 --> 36:04.714
we're gonna deliver
some slashes

36:04.714 --> 36:06.341
on this wild boar carcass.

36:06.341 --> 36:07.551
Joe, Casey, you're up first.
Are you ready?

36:07.551 --> 36:09.678
both: Oh, yeah.

36:09.678 --> 36:11.429
- This is kinda the moment
it's all been boiling down to,

36:11.429 --> 36:13.390
and I'm excited
to see how it performs.

36:13.390 --> 36:15.600
Fist bump?
- Fist bump.

36:15.600 --> 36:17.060
- We're psyched.

36:17.060 --> 36:19.020
- I would love
to wield your weapon,

36:19.020 --> 36:21.690
but I'm still healing
from an injury,

36:21.690 --> 36:25.026
so I'd like to bring in
Anthony Palmer...

36:25.026 --> 36:26.611
♪ ♪

36:26.611 --> 36:28.530
And today, he will be my arm.

36:28.530 --> 36:29.948
Have fun.

36:29.948 --> 36:36.913
♪ ♪

36:48.425 --> 36:52.012
All right, Joe, Casey,
off the bat, it is light.

36:52.012 --> 36:54.180
You got the weight perfect.

36:54.180 --> 36:56.891
On the draw-cut right here,
you can see

36:56.891 --> 36:59.227
that it lacerated easily.

36:59.227 --> 37:00.770
The cut here in the spine,

37:00.770 --> 37:04.357
you can see
all the nice pieces of bacon

37:04.357 --> 37:07.235
that we're gonna make later on
with this particular carcass.

37:07.235 --> 37:09.904
Your blade, it will kill.

37:09.904 --> 37:11.197
Good job, gentlemen.

37:11.197 --> 37:12.824
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

37:12.824 --> 37:14.451
- Mark, Jessica,
you're up next. You ready?

37:14.451 --> 37:15.827
- Definitely.
- Absolutely.

37:15.827 --> 37:17.662
- Let's do this.
- Joe and Casey

37:17.662 --> 37:19.205
got right up into
that ham heart.

37:19.205 --> 37:20.457
- That cut into the ham.
- Yeah.

37:20.457 --> 37:22.125
- Yeah, it went deep.

37:22.125 --> 37:24.002
- Yeah, that was
all the way to the bone.

37:24.002 --> 37:26.463
If we can perform
as good as that, I'm happy.

37:26.463 --> 37:33.386
♪ ♪

37:37.766 --> 37:39.559
[both chuckling]

37:39.559 --> 37:42.145
♪ ♪

37:42.145 --> 37:43.980
- All right, Mark, Jessica,

37:43.980 --> 37:46.316
now, your blade is wider,

37:46.316 --> 37:48.401
but the balance is light.

37:48.401 --> 37:51.946
In this particular slice,
almost cut in half,

37:51.946 --> 37:53.365
but definitely
on the final cut,

37:53.365 --> 37:54.991
glided easily.

37:54.991 --> 37:57.661
Your blade,
it's curvaceous and sexy,

37:57.661 --> 37:59.329
and it will kill.

37:59.329 --> 38:00.664
- [chuckles]
both: Thank you.

38:00.664 --> 38:02.457
- Next up is the strength test.

38:02.457 --> 38:03.458
Ben?

38:03.458 --> 38:05.585
♪ ♪

38:05.585 --> 38:08.171
- Bladesmiths, I'm gonna
take each of your swords

38:08.171 --> 38:10.340
and deliver one
Herculean strike

38:10.340 --> 38:11.716
on this piece of sheet metal

38:11.716 --> 38:13.843
to see how it affects
your blade.

38:13.843 --> 38:15.512
Joe, Casey, you're up.
You ready?

38:15.512 --> 38:17.806
both: Oh, yeah.
- We love to test blades,

38:17.806 --> 38:20.100
and it's killing us right now
to not run over to Ben

38:20.100 --> 38:21.976
and grab the sword
from his hand.

38:21.976 --> 38:28.900
♪ ♪

38:34.239 --> 38:36.574
- This is a beautifully
light sword.

38:36.574 --> 38:37.951
It's very well balanced.

38:37.951 --> 38:39.494
I like the string
wrapped handle.

38:39.494 --> 38:41.121
It's easy to keep
a good grip on it.

38:41.121 --> 38:43.331
The edge took
a little bit of dulling.

38:43.331 --> 38:45.834
There's a piece
of the sheet metal

38:45.834 --> 38:48.128
almost welded onto your blade
from the impact,

38:48.128 --> 38:49.921
but it's still very well done.

38:49.921 --> 38:51.631
both: Thank you.

38:51.631 --> 38:53.049
- Mark, Jessica, you guys
are up. You ready?

38:53.049 --> 38:54.509
- Indeed.
- All right.

38:54.509 --> 38:56.845
- After seeing Joe and Casey's,

38:56.845 --> 38:59.180
I'm thinking,
"Did I over-harden it?

38:59.180 --> 39:01.641
Is it going to break?"

39:01.641 --> 39:03.309
My heart is in my throat.

39:03.309 --> 39:04.811
- It's terrifying.

39:04.811 --> 39:06.519
♪ ♪

39:10.447 --> 39:13.784
Ben is about to do
something to this blade

39:13.784 --> 39:16.203
that should never be done.

39:16.203 --> 39:17.829
- Slamming it
into a steel plate.

39:17.829 --> 39:19.081
- Steel--[chuckles, sighs]
- Dear Lord.

39:19.081 --> 39:20.666
Why would you do that?

39:20.666 --> 39:27.130
♪ ♪

39:28.799 --> 39:31.385
♪ ♪

39:31.385 --> 39:34.346
- Mark, Jessica, this is
a beautiful sword to wield.

39:34.346 --> 39:37.140
It's so comfortable.
It's so well balanced.

39:37.140 --> 39:39.101
The steel did a little number
on your sword, though.

39:39.101 --> 39:40.978
There's a chip right there.

39:40.978 --> 39:43.438
But, uh, for such
a light and fast weapon

39:43.438 --> 39:45.065
as both of these are, actually,

39:45.065 --> 39:48.068
it's amazing that
they got away this unscathed.

39:48.068 --> 39:50.153
Very well done.
both: Thank you.

39:50.153 --> 39:51.571
- Next up
is the sharpness test,

39:51.571 --> 39:52.906
and for that,
I'll give you to Dave.

39:52.906 --> 39:55.158
♪ ♪

39:55.158 --> 39:56.660
- To test the edge
of your blade

39:56.660 --> 39:58.578
to see if it's retained
that edge,

39:58.578 --> 40:00.288
I'll be cutting through
these water tubes.

40:00.288 --> 40:02.040
Joe, Casey, you guys ready?

40:02.040 --> 40:03.542
- Oh, yeah.
- Let's go for it.

40:03.542 --> 40:10.424
♪ ♪

40:15.012 --> 40:19.099
- Joe, Casey, your sword has
a great feel to it.

40:19.099 --> 40:20.851
I like the shape of the grip.

40:20.851 --> 40:23.478
But there's that section
where that edge is rolled,

40:23.478 --> 40:25.897
and that's where
the cut started.

40:25.897 --> 40:28.150
You can see that first tube
kinda crushed.

40:28.150 --> 40:29.860
Then, it starts to cut,

40:29.860 --> 40:32.237
as I get up into the sharper
section up in here.

40:32.237 --> 40:33.864
By then, everything is
pushed over,

40:33.864 --> 40:35.532
and kinda crushed
that last tube.

40:35.532 --> 40:36.950
It's a beautiful piece.
Well done.

40:36.950 --> 40:38.493
- Thanks.
- Thanks.

40:38.493 --> 40:39.453
- All right, Mark, Jessica,
you ready?

40:39.453 --> 40:40.412
- Indeed.
- Yes.

40:40.412 --> 40:41.455
- Okay.

40:41.455 --> 40:48.378
♪ ♪

40:53.967 --> 40:55.761
- Good job.

40:55.761 --> 40:57.345
- So, Mark, Jessica,

40:57.345 --> 40:59.431
you maintained
a bit more of an edge here.

40:59.431 --> 41:01.141
As you can see,
that cut travels through there.

41:01.141 --> 41:03.060
They're clean across the tops.

41:03.060 --> 41:04.394
Didn't blow out
any of the tubes.

41:04.394 --> 41:05.812
Didn't crush any of them.

41:05.812 --> 41:08.398
Anyway, uh,
beautifully made piece.

41:08.398 --> 41:10.150
It's definitely a cutter.
Nicely done.

41:10.150 --> 41:12.319
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

41:12.319 --> 41:14.321
♪ ♪

41:14.321 --> 41:16.948
- Bladesmiths, your Chinese Dao
have been tested,

41:16.948 --> 41:19.785
and the judges have evaluated
the finer details of your work,

41:19.785 --> 41:22.287
and they've made
their final decision.

41:22.287 --> 41:24.539
The "Forged in Fire"
champions are...

41:24.539 --> 41:26.500
♪ ♪

41:26.500 --> 41:28.668
Mark and Jessica,
congratulations,

41:28.668 --> 41:31.213
you are the "Forged in Fire"
champions.

41:31.213 --> 41:34.216
Joe and Casey, your weapon
did not make the cut.

41:34.216 --> 41:36.301
David Baker's
gonna tell you why.

41:36.301 --> 41:38.970
- Joe, Casey, you brought us
back a Chinese Dao

41:38.970 --> 41:41.056
that I personally
would be proud to own,

41:41.056 --> 41:42.682
and it was a real
pleasure using it.

41:42.682 --> 41:44.768
But in our kill test
on the boar carcass,

41:44.768 --> 41:47.562
and on the sharpness test
on the water tubes,

41:47.562 --> 41:50.148
your weapon just didn't perform
as well as your competitor,

41:50.148 --> 41:52.484
and for that simple reason,
we've gotta let you go.

41:52.484 --> 41:54.194
♪ ♪

41:54.194 --> 41:56.154
- Joe, Casey,
please surrender your blade.

41:56.154 --> 41:57.781
♪ ♪

41:57.781 --> 42:00.117
- We lost fair and square...
- Mm-hmm.

42:00.117 --> 42:01.827
- But I couldn't have asked
for a better week of learning.

42:01.827 --> 42:03.995
- Casey's an amazing
apprentice.

42:03.995 --> 42:06.081
I have no doubt he'll be
an amazing master also.

42:06.081 --> 42:08.250
- Do I get a cap and gown?

42:08.250 --> 42:10.127
- [chuckles] If I had one,
I'd give you one.

42:10.127 --> 42:11.586
- Do I get a diploma
with the crayon written on it?

42:11.586 --> 42:13.797
- Tell you what,
you get the stuff

42:13.797 --> 42:14.881
and give it to me, and then
I'll give it back to you.

42:14.881 --> 42:16.466
- Okay. Perfect.

42:16.466 --> 42:18.468
♪ ♪

42:18.468 --> 42:20.554
- Mark, Jessica,
you are our new

42:20.554 --> 42:22.722
"Forged in Fire" champions,

42:22.722 --> 42:24.057
and that's a title that comes
with a check for ten grand.

42:24.057 --> 42:25.475
Congratulations.

42:25.475 --> 42:27.477
- I'm blown away.
- It's that time.

42:27.477 --> 42:30.897
Please present your weapon
to the judges.

42:30.897 --> 42:34.317
- It's the finish of the
biggest roller coaster ever.

42:34.317 --> 42:38.071
The training that Jessica
has gone through works,

42:38.071 --> 42:41.283
and it can turn somebody
into one heck of a smith.

42:41.283 --> 42:42.951
It's amazing.
- [chuckles]

42:42.951 --> 42:44.411
- It's gonna take a while
for this to sink in,

42:44.411 --> 42:45.745
without a doubt.

42:45.745 --> 42:51.168
♪ ♪

42:51.168 --> 42:52.544
[metallic clank]
